## Declaring a Module: `export module`

A file becomes a **module interface unit** when it starts with:

```cpp
export module module_name;
```

The module name is an identifier (or several separated by dots, e.g. `mylib.math`). This declaration must be the first "real" declaration in the file (only a global module fragment `module;` may precede it, see below).

## What to Export: `export`

By default, everything declared in a module is **visible only inside** it. To make something available to importers, mark it with `export`:

```cpp
export module mylib;           // declare the module

export int square(int x) { return x * x; }     // export a function
export class Point { /*...*/ };                // export a class
export template<typename T> T identity(T v) { return v; }  // a template

int helper() { return 42; }   // NOT exported — internal detail
```

You can export an entire **namespace**:

```cpp
export namespace math {
    double pi() { return 3.14159265; }
    double e()  { return 2.71828182; }
    // all names inside become public
}
```

Or use an **export block** to group declarations:

```cpp
export {
    void foo();
    void bar();
    int baz = 42;
}
```

## Importing: `import`

```cpp
import mylib;          // import the module

int main() {
    auto p = square(5);    // OK: square is exported
    // helper();           // error: helper is not exported
}
```

`import` is fundamentally different from `#include`: the compiler reads a pre-compiled **Binary Module Interface** (BMI) rather than re-parsing the source. This is why modules speed up compilation.

## The Global Module Fragment: `module;`

If a module needs to use legacy headers, they go into the **global module fragment** — a special section before the module declaration:

```cpp
module;                    // start of global fragment
#include <cmath>           // legacy #include only allowed here
#include <cstring>
#define BUFFER_SIZE 256    // macro stays inside this file only

export module mylib;       // module declaration (ends global fragment)

export double safe_sqrt(double x) {
    return x >= 0 ? std::sqrt(x) : 0.0;
}
```

Key property: macros from `#include` in the global fragment **do not leak** to importers. Code that writes `import mylib;` does not see `BUFFER_SIZE` or macros from `<cmath>`. This solves the macro pollution problem.

## The Private Fragment: `module :private;`

At the end of a file you can add a **private module fragment** — a section completely hidden from importers, including its names. It is useful for two things:

1. Placing code that should not affect the interface (implementations in large modules).
2. In learning examples: adding `main()` to the same file as the interface.

```cpp
export module mylib;
export int answer() { return 42; }

module :private;   // everything below is not part of the interface

#include <iostream>
int main() {
    std::cout << answer() << "\n";
}
```

## Module Interface Unit vs. Implementation Unit

In a real project, a large module is typically split into two files:

```
// math.cppm  — module interface unit
export module math;
export int square(int x);
export double cube(double x);
```

```
// math.cpp  — module implementation unit
module math;       // declare belonging to module, no export
int square(int x) { return x * x; }
double cube(double x) { return x * x * x; }
```

Importers only need the interface unit. The implementation unit is part of the same module but its contents are hidden.

## Exporting Templates and Concepts

Templates in modules work better than in headers: the template definition stays in the interface unit (the compiler still needs it for instantiation), but it is **not re-parsed** with every `import`. Concepts are also fully supported:

```cpp
export module containers;

export template<typename T>
requires std::totally_ordered<T>
class SortedVec { /*...*/ };

export template<typename T>
concept Printable = requires(T t) { std::cout << t; };
```

## Comparing `#include` and `import`

| Feature | `#include` | `import` |
|---|---|---|
| Re-parsed each time | yes | no (BMI) |
| Macros leak | yes | no |
| Dependency order | implicit | explicit |
| Compatibility | all compilers | C++20+ |
| Incremental build | weak | good |

examples.code:
module;
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>

export module mathlib;

// Export an individual function
export int square(int x) { return x * x; }

// Export an entire namespace — all its names become public
export namespace math {
    int cube(int x) { return x * x * x; }
    double pi() { return 3.14159265358979; }
}

// NOT exported — internal helper, inaccessible from outside
int internal_helper(int x) { return x + 1; }

// Export a class
export class Point {
public:
    int x, y;
    Point(int x, int y) : x(x), y(y) {}
    std::string str() const {
        return "(" + std::to_string(x) + ", " + std::to_string(y) + ")";
    }
};

module :private;

int main() {
    std::cout << "square(5) = " << square(5) << "\n";
    std::cout << "math::cube(3) = " << math::cube(3) << "\n";
    std::cout << "math::pi() = " << math::pi() << "\n";

    Point p{3, 4};
    std::cout << "Point: " << p.str() << "\n";

    // internal_helper is visible in the private fragment (same TU)
    std::cout << "internal_helper(10) = " << internal_helper(10) << "\n";

    return 0;
}

module;
// Global fragment: only legacy #includes are allowed here
// Macros declared here do NOT leak to importers
#define INTERNAL_MAX(a,b) ((a)>(b)?(a):(b))
#include <iostream>
#include <algorithm>

export module safemath;

export int clamp_value(int val, int lo, int hi) {
    // INTERNAL_MAX is visible here (same translation unit)
    return std::clamp(val, lo, hi);
}

export int absolute(int x) {
    return x < 0 ? -x : x;
}

module :private;

int main() {
    std::cout << "clamp_value(15, 0, 10) = " << clamp_value(15, 0, 10) << "\n";
    std::cout << "clamp_value(-5, 0, 10) = " << clamp_value(-5, 0, 10) << "\n";
    std::cout << "absolute(-42) = " << absolute(-42) << "\n";

    // INTERNAL_MAX is visible in the private fragment (same TU)
    std::cout << "INTERNAL_MAX(3, 7) = " << INTERNAL_MAX(3, 7) << "\n";

    // If we wrote: import safemath;  — INTERNAL_MAX would be inaccessible.
    // This is module macro isolation.

    return 0;
}

module;
#include <iostream>
#include <concepts>
#include <string>

export module containers;

// Template exported with full definition — instantiation is possible at the importer
export template<typename T>
requires std::totally_ordered<T>
class MinStack {
    T data_[64];
    int size_ = 0;
public:
    void push(T val) { data_[size_++] = val; }
    T pop()  { return data_[--size_]; }
    T peek() const { return data_[size_ - 1]; }
    bool empty() const { return size_ == 0; }
};

// Export a concept
export template<typename T>
concept Printable = requires(T t) {
    { std::cout << t };
};

// Export a function template constrained by the concept
export template<Printable T>
void println(const T& val) {
    std::cout << val << "\n";
}

module :private;

int main() {
    MinStack<int> stack;
    stack.push(5);
    stack.push(2);
    stack.push(8);
    std::cout << "top: " << stack.peek() << "\n";
    std::cout << "pop: " << stack.pop() << "\n";
    std::cout << "top: " << stack.peek() << "\n";

    println(42);
    println(std::string("hello from module template"));

    return 0;
}

