## Module Partitions

When a module grows large, it can be split into **partitions**. Each partition is a separate file named `module:partition`:

```cpp
// math:algebra.cppm — the algebra partition of the math module
export module math:algebra;

export int gcd(int a, int b) {
    while (b) { int t = b; b = a % b; a = t; }
    return a;
}
export int lcm(int a, int b) { return a / gcd(a, b) * b; }
```

```cpp
// math:geometry.cppm — the geometry partition
export module math:geometry;

export double circle_area(double r) { return 3.14159 * r * r; }
export double hypotenuse(double a, double b) {
    return __builtin_sqrt(a*a + b*b);
}
```

The primary interface unit gathers partitions via `export import`:

```cpp
// math.cppm — primary interface unit
export module math;

export import :algebra;   // re-export the algebra partition
export import :geometry;  // re-export the geometry partition
```

An importer just writes `import math;` and gets everything: `gcd`, `lcm`, `circle_area`, `hypotenuse`. Partitions are not visible as standalone entities from the outside.

### Internal (non-exported) partitions

A partition can be **internal** — not part of the public interface, only used in the implementation:

```cpp
// math:impl.cppm — internal partition (no export before module)
module math:impl;     // belongs to module, but not re-exported

void internal_compute() { /*...*/ }
```

The primary unit or other partitions import it via `import :impl;` (without `export`).

## Re-export: `export import`

`export import` makes the contents of another module or partition visible to importers of the **current** module:

```cpp
export module myapp;
export import :core;     // re-export an internal partition
export import :utils;    // another partition
export import helpers;   // re-export another module entirely
```

An importer of `myapp` automatically sees everything that is re-exported. Without `export` — `import :core;` — the partition is only visible inside `myapp`.

## The Private Fragment: `module :private;`

The private fragment is a section in the **primary** interface unit separated by `module :private;`. Everything after this line is not part of the public interface:

```cpp
export module mylib;
export void foo();        // public
void bar();               // visible only inside mylib (not exported)

module :private;
// bar() definition — completely hidden from importers
void bar() { /*...*/ }

// Key: changes in :private do NOT require re-compiling importers.
// Only the primary unit's BMI matters to them.
```

**Key property**: if you change only the private fragment (the implementation, without changing declarations in the interface section), re-compiling importers is **not required**. The BMI does not change.

## Header Units: `import <vector>;`

C++20 allows importing standard headers as modules:

```cpp
import <vector>;    // instead of #include <vector>
import <string>;    // instead of #include <string>
import <iostream>;  // instead of #include <iostream>
```

Technically this creates a "header unit" — a pre-compiled representation of the header. Benefits:
- the header is parsed once,
- macros from the header still propagate (this distinguishes header units from proper named modules).

Header unit support in 2024 is unstable: Clang supports them, MSVC — partially, GCC — with flags. Most projects still use `#include`.

## `import std;` — the entire standard library as one module (C++23)

C++23 adds standard named modules:

```cpp
import std;         // the entire standard library
import std.compat;  // + C-compatible names (printf, etc.)
```

```cpp
// Instead of:
#include <vector>
#include <string>
#include <algorithm>
#include <iostream>

// Just write:
import std;
```

This works in MSVC 17.5+, GCC 14+, Clang 17+ (experimental). `import std;` is compiled once and then used as a single BMI — this radically speeds up builds of projects that previously pulled full headers into every `.cpp`.

## Practical Constraints and Migration Path

Why most projects in 2024 are not on modules:

1. **Build system requirements**: CMake added module support in version 3.28 (December 2023). Meson, Bazel — significantly later. Most legacy projects use older CMake versions or custom build systems.

2. **Compilation order dependency**: `#include` allows compiling files in any order. Modules require that the interface unit be compiled before all importers — the build system must enforce this.

3. **Compatibility with existing code**: thousands of libraries ship headers only. Transition is only possible once their authors add module support.

**Realistic migration path**:
- Write new code with `export module`.
- Hide legacy headers in the global fragment (`module;` … `export module`).
- Add `import std;` when the compiler/build system supports it.
- Don't rush: `#include` is not going away anytime soon.

## File Extensions and Conventions

The standard does not fix the extension for module interface units. In practice:

| Compiler/ecosystem | Interface extension | Implementation |
|---|---|---|
| MSVC / Visual Studio | `.ixx` | `.cpp` |
| GCC / Clang | `.cppm` or `.cxx` | `.cpp` |
| CMake (recommended) | `.cppm` | `.cpp` |

Ordinary `.cpp` files with `module foo;` (without `export`) are implementation units — their extension remains `.cpp`.

examples.code:
// In a real project this would be split into partitions:
//   module analytics:stats   (Stats, compute_stats)
//   module analytics:io      (print_stats)
//   module analytics         (export import :stats; export import :io; + filter)
// Here everything is in one file to demonstrate the public interface.
module;
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <algorithm>
#include <numeric>
#include <string>

export module analytics;

export struct Stats {
    double mean;
    double min_val;
    double max_val;
    int count;
};

export Stats compute_stats(const std::vector<double>& data) {
    if (data.empty()) return {0, 0, 0, 0};
    double sum = std::accumulate(data.begin(), data.end(), 0.0);
    auto [mn, mx] = std::minmax_element(data.begin(), data.end());
    return {sum / data.size(), *mn, *mx, static_cast<int>(data.size())};
}

export void print_stats(const Stats& s) {
    std::cout << "count=" << s.count
              << "  mean=" << s.mean
              << "  min=" << s.min_val
              << "  max=" << s.max_val << "\n";
}

// Export a template — full definition here, instantiation at the importer
export template<typename T, typename Pred>
std::vector<T> filter(const std::vector<T>& v, Pred pred) {
    std::vector<T> result;
    std::copy_if(v.begin(), v.end(), std::back_inserter(result), pred);
    return result;
}

module :private;

int main() {
    std::vector<double> data = {3.0, 1.5, 4.2, 1.5, 9.1, 2.6, 5.3, 8.9, 7.9, 3.2};

    std::cout << "All data:\n  ";
    print_stats(compute_stats(data));

    auto positives = filter(data, [](double x){ return x > 5.0; });
    std::cout << "Values > 5.0:\n  ";
    print_stats(compute_stats(positives));

    return 0;
}

// Demonstrates what is part of the module 'interface' (affects the BMI)
// and what is an 'implementation detail' (in :private, does not affect BMI).
module;
#include <cmath>
#include <iostream>
#include <stdexcept>

export module geometry;

export constexpr double PI = 3.14159265358979323846;

export struct Circle {
    double radius;
    explicit Circle(double r) {
        if (r <= 0) throw std::invalid_argument("radius must be positive");
        radius = r;
    }
    double area()          const { return PI * radius * radius; }
    double circumference() const { return 2.0 * PI * radius; }
};

export struct Rectangle {
    double width, height;
    double area()     const { return width * height; }
    double diagonal() const { return std::sqrt(width*width + height*height); }
};

export double degrees_to_radians(double deg) {
    return deg * PI / 180.0;
}

module :private;
// Everything below is private implementation.
// Changes here do NOT require re-compiling files that wrote import geometry.

int main() {
    Circle c{5.0};
    std::cout << "Circle r=5:\n";
    std::cout << "  area = " << c.area() << "\n";
    std::cout << "  circumference = " << c.circumference() << "\n";

    Rectangle r{3.0, 4.0};
    std::cout << "Rectangle 3x4:\n";
    std::cout << "  area = " << r.area() << "\n";
    std::cout << "  diagonal = " << r.diagonal() << "\n";

    std::cout << "45 degrees = " << degrees_to_radians(45.0) << " radians\n";

    try {
        Circle bad{-1.0};
    } catch (const std::invalid_argument& e) {
        std::cout << "caught: " << e.what() << "\n";
    }

    return 0;
}
